(40, 13, 22, 42, 8, 14, 14, 'the care of this world, and the deceitfulness of riches', 'Connection of Thorns and Unfruitfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the choking effect of worldly cares and riches on spiritual growth, leading to unfruitfulness. They illustrate a similar warning about the dangers of distractions in life.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 22, 54, 6, 9, 10, 'care of this world', 'Connection of Worldly Concerns', 'Both passages emphasize the dangers of worldly desires and the pursuit of wealth. Matthew warns that the ''care of this world'' can choke the word, while 1 Timothy highlights how the desire to be rich leads to temptation and sorrow.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 22, 41, 4, 18, 19, 'the care of this world, and the deceitfulness of riches', 'Connection of Thorns and Unfruitfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the impact of worldly cares and deceitfulness of riches on spiritual fruitfulness. They describe how these distractions can choke the word, leading to unfruitfulness.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 22, 42, 12, 15, 15, 'care of this world', 'Connection of Worldly Concerns', 'Both passages emphasize the dangers of worldly concerns and materialism. Matthew warns that the ''care of this world'' can render one unfruitful, while Luke cautions against ''covetousness'' and the misconception that life is defined by possessions.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 22, 21, 5, 10, 11, 'deceitfulness of riches', 'Connection of Wealth and Unfruitfulness', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of pursuing wealth and material abundance. In Matthew, the ''deceitfulness of riches'' leads to unfruitfulness, while Ecclesiastes highlights that loving silver brings dissatisfaction and vanity.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 22, 55, 4, 10, 10, 'the care of this world', 'Connection of Worldly Concerns', 'Both passages emphasize the dangers of loving the present world, which leads to unfruitfulness. In Matthew, the cares of this world choke the word, while in 2 Timothy, Demas forsakes Paul due to his love for the present world.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 23, 50, 1, 11, 11, NULL, 'Fruits of Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of bearing fruit in both passages. Matthew emphasizes the fruitful response to the word, while Philippians speaks of being filled with the fruits of righteousness.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 23, 40, 12, 33, 33, NULL, 'Connection of Fruitfulness and Goodness', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of fruit as a reflection of one''s inner state. The good ground in Matthew 13:23 produces good fruit, while Matthew 12:33 discusses making the tree good to yield good fruit.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 23, 43, 15, 16, 16, NULL, 'Fruitfulness in Discipleship', 'This connection highlights the theme of bearing fruit in both passages. Matthew emphasizes understanding the word and producing fruit, while John speaks of being chosen to bring forth fruit that remains.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 23, 48, 5, 22, 23, NULL, 'Connection of Fruit and Growth', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''fruit'' in both passages. Matthew discusses the fruit borne from understanding the word, while Galatians describes the fruit of the Spirit, emphasizing the growth and manifestation of spiritual qualities.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 23, 19, 92, 13, 15, NULL, 'Fruitfulness in God''s Presence', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of bearing fruit as a result of being rooted in God''s word and presence. The good ground in Matthew leads to fruitful outcomes, while Psalms highlights flourishing and fruitfulness for those planted in the house of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 23, 40, 13, 8, 8, 'good ground', 'Connection of Good Ground', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''good ground'' and its role in producing fruit. They highlight the varying degrees of fruitfulness, indicating a shared theme of receptivity to the word.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 23, 43, 15, 1, 8, NULL, 'Fruitfulness in Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of bearing fruit as a sign of true discipleship. In Matthew, the good ground produces fruit, while in John, abiding in the vine leads to much fruit.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 24, 40, 25, 1, 1, 'the kingdom of heaven', 'Connection of the Kingdom of Heaven', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''the kingdom of heaven'' and illustrate different aspects of its nature. The first passage describes the sowing of good seed, while the second introduces the readiness of the virgins in anticipation of the bridegroom, highlighting the importance of preparation within the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 24, 40, 13, 47, 47, 'kingdom of heaven', 'Connection of Kingdom Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of the kingdom of heaven through agricultural and fishing metaphors. The good seed and the net symbolize the gathering of people into God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 24, 42, 13, 20, 20, 'the kingdom of heaven', 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the kingdom, with Matthew describing it as a man sowing good seed and Luke asking how to liken the kingdom of God. This connection highlights the teaching about the nature of the kingdom in parabolic form.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 24, 41, 4, 26, 30, 'the kingdom of heaven is likened unto', 'Kingdom of God Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the process of sowing seed as a metaphor for the kingdom of God. They illustrate the growth and eventual harvest that follows the initial planting, highlighting the natural progression of the kingdom''s development.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 24, 60, 1, 23, 23, 'good seed', 'Connection of Seed Imagery', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''seed'' in both passages, where Matthew speaks of ''good seed'' representing the kingdom of heaven, while 1 Peter contrasts ''corruptible seed'' with ''incorruptible'' seed, emphasizing the enduring nature of God''s word. Both passages emphasize the transformative power of the seed in relation to spiritual life.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 24, 51, 1, 5, 5, 'kingdom of heaven', 'Kingdom of Heaven and Hope', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of heaven as a place of promise and hope. Both passages emphasize the idea of something good being sown or laid up for believers in a heavenly context.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 24, 7, 14, 12, 13, NULL, 'Riddles and Seeds in Parables', 'This connection highlights the use of metaphorical language in both passages. The ''good seed'' in Matthew represents a deeper truth, similar to how Samson''s riddle serves to reveal hidden meanings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 25, 60, 5, 8, 8, 'while men slept', 'Vigilance Against Spiritual Adversaries', 'Both passages emphasize the need for vigilance against an enemy who seeks to undermine. In Matthew, the enemy sows tares while men sleep, while in 1 Peter, the devil is depicted as seeking to devour. This connection highlights the importance of being alert to spiritual threats.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 25, 61, 2, 1, 1, NULL, 'Falsehood Among the Faithful', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of deceit among the faithful. In Matthew, the enemy sows tares among the wheat, while in 2 Peter, false teachers secretly introduce heresies. This connection highlights the danger of hidden threats within a community.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 25, 40, 13, 39, 39, 'his enemy came and sowed tares', 'Connection Between Enemy and Harvest', 'This connection highlights the role of the enemy in both passages. The enemy who sows tares is identified as the devil, linking the act of sowing with the ultimate judgment at the harvest.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 25, 44, 20, 30, 31, NULL, 'Warning Against Deception', 'Both passages emphasize the danger of enemies sowing discord among believers. In Matthew, the enemy sows tares, while in Acts, men arise to draw disciples away. This connection highlights the need for vigilance against false teachings.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 25, 58, 12, 15, 15, NULL, 'Bitterness and Tares Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of negative influences in both passages. In Matthew, the enemy sows tares among the wheat, while Hebrews warns against a root of bitterness springing up, both leading to defilement.', 'theme', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 25, 66, 12, 9, 9, 'his enemy came and sowed tares', 'Deception and Adversarial Action', 'Both passages emphasize the role of an enemy who sows discord. In Matthew, the enemy sows tares among the wheat, while in Revelation, the Devil deceives the whole world, illustrating a common theme of spiritual opposition.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 13, 25, 40, 25, 5, 5, NULL, 'Sleep and Vigilance Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the state of sleeping, highlighting a lack of vigilance. In Matthew 13:25, the sleeping men allow the enemy to sow tares, while in Matthew 25:5, the bridegroom''s delay leads to all slumbering.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
